This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a method to reduce the computational demands of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for various tasks. It also mentions the use of the ILSVRC-2012 dataset, which is commonly used in computer vision research. 

The paper also involves machine learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a method to dynamically predict zero-valued activations in CNNs. 

Artificial intelligence (cs.AI) is another likely sub-category as the paper proposes a method to optimize the performance of CNNs, which are commonly used in AI applications. 

Neural networks (cs.NE) is also a possible sub-category as the paper focuses on reducing the number of convolution operations in CNNs, which are a type of neural network. 

Finally, multimedia (cs.MM) is a less likely sub-category as the paper involves processing visual data, which is a type of multimedia.
